## Propagating Trace Context Across RabbitMQ

The key is to inject the current trace context into message headers on publish, then extract it on consume to link the spans.

**Publisher (Service A):**

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;
using OpenTelemetry;
using OpenTelemetry.Context.Propagation;
using RabbitMQ.Client;

// Create an ActivitySource for your publisher
private static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");
private static readonly TextMapPropagator Propagator = Propagators.DefaultTextMapPropagator;

public void PublishOrder(OrderEvent order, IModel channel)
{
    using var activity = Source.StartActivity("order.publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

    var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
    props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

    // Inject trace context into message headers
    Propagator.Inject(
        new PropagationContext(activity.Context, Baggage.Current),
        props.Headers,
        (headers, key, value) => headers[key] = value);

    var body = JsonSerializer.SerializeToUtf8Bytes(order);
    channel.BasicPublish("orders-exchange", "order.created", props, body);
}
```

**Consumer (Service B):**

```csharp
private static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");
private static readonly TextMapPropagator Propagator = Propagators.DefaultTextMapPropagator;

public void HandleMessage(BasicDeliverEventArgs ea)
{
    // Extract context from headers
    var parentContext = Propagator.Extract(
        default,
        ea.BasicProperties.Headers,
        (headers, key) =>
        {
            if (headers != null && headers.TryGetValue(key, out var value))
            {
                return new[] { Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])value) };
            }
            return Enumerable.Empty<string>();
        });

    Baggage.Current = parentContext.Baggage;

    // Start a linked activity — this continues the distributed trace
    using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
        "order.process",
        ActivityKind.Consumer,
        parentContext.ActivityContext);

    // Process the message — any downstream spans are now parented correctly
    var order = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<OrderEvent>(ea.Body.Span);
    ProcessOrder(order);
}
```

**OpenTelemetry setup (both services):**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(tracing => tracing
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")  // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

**Why this works:** RabbitMQ headers are byte arrays, so the extract lambda must decode them. The `PropagationContext` carries the W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers, letting the consumer create a child span under the producer's trace. Your backend (Jaeger, Tempo, etc.) then stitches both services into one end-to-end trace.
